The paper deals with algorithmic and computational aspects of multiwinner voting problems with fairness constraints. This makes it likely to belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories, which often deal with algorithmic and computational aspects of voting and preference aggregation problems. The paper also proposes a general algorithmic framework that can be used with any score function, which makes it relevant to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also studies the complexity of the problem for monotone submodular score functions, which makes it relevant to the Data Structures (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with fairness constraints with respect to multiple, non-disjoint attributes, which makes it relevant to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category.
